The two pipelines side by side, with a comparison table at the bottom. Clic=
k any node to dive deeper into that component.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal">The co=
re changes when going from 4 =E2=86=92 10,000 documents:</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal"><stron=
g>Ingest layer</strong> =E2=80=94 swap serial processing for a task queue (=
Celery/Airflow). Each doc gets chunked and embedded in parallel workers, cu=
tting ingest from hours to minutes.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal"><stron=
g>Embeddings</strong> =E2=80=94 move from a local sentence-transformer to a=
 batched API call (OpenAI or Cohere). You get better quality and GPU-level =
throughput without running your own model server.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal"><stron=
g>Vector store</strong> =E2=80=94 ChromaDB is great for local dev but store=
s everything in-process. At 10K docs you need a managed ANN index (Pinecone=
, Weaviate, or Qdrant) that runs approximate nearest-neighbor search with h=
orizontal scaling and persistence.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal"><stron=
g>Retrieval</strong> =E2=80=94 dense-only search starts failing on financia=
l terms ("EBITDA", "TSMC CoWoS capacity"). A hybrid retriever combines dens=
e vectors with BM25 keyword matching, then a cross-encoder reranker re-scor=
es the top 20 candidates before passing 3=E2=80=935 to the LLM.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal"><stron=
g>Caching</strong> =E2=80=94 prompt caching on the LLM layer means repeated=
 similar queries (e.g. "What is NVIDIA's moat?" in slightly different forms=
) reuse cached context and drop latency from ~2s to ~200ms.</p></div></div>=
